, surprisingly little has been written about how this political formation is lived. For Love of the Prophet looks at the Republic of Sudan's twenty-five-year experiment with Islamic statehood. Focusing not on state institutions, but rather on the daily life that goes on in their shadows, Noah Salomon's careful ethnography examines the lasting effects of state Islamization on Sudanese society through a study of the individuals and organizations working in its midst.Salomon investigates Sudan at a crucial moment in its history-balanced between unity and partition, secular and religious politics, peace and war-when those who desired an Islamic state were rethinking the political form under which they had lived for nearly a generation. Countering the dominant discourse, Salomon depicts contemporary Islamic politics not as a response to secularism and Westernization but as a node in a much longer conversation within Islamic thought, augmented and reappropriated as state projects of Islamic reform became objects of debate and controversy.Among the first books to delve into the making of the modern Islamic state, For Love of the Prophet reveals both novel political ideals and new articulations of Islam as it is rethought through the lens of the nation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aIslam and politicszSudan. 0aIslam and statezSudan. 0aIslamzSudan. 0aIslamic lawzSudan. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aBritish colonialism.  aISIS.  aInqadh regime.  aIslam.  aIslamic governance.  aIslamic politics.  aIslamic state project.  aIslamic state.  aIslamization.  aMahdist Islamic political order.  aNational Congress Party.  aNational Unity.  aSudan People's Liberation Movement.  aSudan.  aSudanese politics.  aSudanese society.  aSudanese students.  aWesterni